Saudi Arabia Real Estate (AQAR), Rental house for Riyadh, Jeddah, Dammam, and Alkhobar Data Analysis¶

This document analyze a dataset containing features and prices for 3718 houses from three main/ largest cities in Saudi Arabia.The chosen cities are Riyadh, Jeddah, Dammam, and Al-Khobar

Problem Definition¶

  • One of the most important things the tenant care about when renting a house is the rental costs( price ), besides its features such as location, size, number of rooms, Whether the property is furnished, Also, electrical goods such as AC are included in the price and so on.

  • So the goal of the tenant is to find the most suitable house that meets its need at a minimal price.

  • In this analysis, We will help tenants to know what is the most factors that affect the rental house price in Saudi Arabia, by examining The provided Aqar data set in order to come up with insights.

  • Visualizing the insights and the relationships that we found between the features and price to the tenants will help them better to decide what are things( features) they require to be supplied in the rental property according to what they can pay.

  • The following questions are to answer during this analysis :

    1. Highest rental house price in Riyadh, Jeddah, Dammam, Khobar, and its features
    2. How the price related to the size?
    3. How much does the oldest and the newest house costs, does the price affected by the age of the property( does the costs of the new house higher or lower than the oldest ones with the same features )
    4. How the number of rooms(in total) affects the price of the rental house, and how does each of the bedrooms, bathrooms, livingrooms number affects the price as well?
    5. is the furnished houses have high prices?
    6. Is there a strong relationships between price and the other features: pool & frontyard & elevator & fireplace & location &garage &ac
    7. does the existence of the 2 features together: driver_room,maid_room affects the price
    8. if the rent house is duplex , how that impact the price?
  • As house price prediction is an important financial decision for individuals or families, House prices can be predicted by the features of rental houses. we use a predictive model to support our analysis by creating a linear regression model that is able to estimate the price of the house accurately given the features.

  • Correlation analysis deals with relationships among variables. The correlation coefficient is a measure of the linear association between two variables, its value is always between -1 and +1.
  • A correlation coefficient of +1 refers to that the two variables are related in a positive linear sense, -1 refers to that the two variables are related in a negative linear sense, and 0 refers to that there is no linear relationship between the two variables.
  • From the above graph, we notice that the driver room, ac,pool and basement have a relatively strong positive relation with price.

Quality issues¶

1. Converting datatype ,A data type of the 'city' and 'front' columns is int, should be catogrical.
2. Removing the outliers in size ,which is does not make sense (very larg size & low price)
3. Renaming the columns ( kitchen, bedrooms','bathrooms', 'livingrooms', furnished,duplex  , ac,bool ,roof ,bool ,frontyard , basement ,elevator,fireplace ) to be descriptive names.
4. Dropping any duplicated rows .
5. Converting Arabic cities names and front names into English, So it is neat and tidy when visualizing it

Tidiness issues¶

6. Dropping unnecessary columns which will not be used in the analysis, which are : 'details' and 'stairs', Details is a text feature and we will not go through the text analysis and the stairs will exist normally if the elevator in not exist.
7. Creating variable for the numbers of rooms , by summing the following features (bedrooms ,bathrooms,livingrooms and kitchen )
8. Creating boolean variable to show if there are driver_room and maid_room , to exmain its relation with the price

House Price Prediction¶

Categorical variables require special attention in regression analysis because, unlike dichotomous or continuous variables, they cannot by entered into the regression equation just as they are. Instead, they need to be recoded into a series of variables which can then be entered into the regression model

In [57]:
#Encode
#In the above data frame, we have a categorical variable, so we need to add dummy variables instead.
var_to_dummy = clean_data[['city']]
dummies = pd.get_dummies(data=var_to_dummy,drop_first=True) #this code added the dummy variable in form of 0 and 1, which is easy to interpret for the regression model.
clean_data.drop(columns=['city','district','front'],inplace=True)
# Drop column as it is now encoded
#data_df = data_df.drop('vehicleType',axis = 1)
#Join the encoded df
clean_data = clean_data.join(dummies)

In [62]:
from sklearn import metrics

def model_scores(true, predicted):  
    mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, predicted)
    mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted)
    rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted))
    r2_square = metrics.r2_score(true, predicted)
    print('MAE:', mae)
    print('MSE:', mse)
    print('RMSE:', rmse)
    print('R2 Square', r2_square , 'It means our model is accurate up to ',r2_square,'% of the time.')
    print('__________________________________')
